question:
Christopher has made a building out of blocks. The grid on the right shows the number of blocks in each part of the building, when viewed from above. Which of the following gives the view you see when you look at Christopher's building from the front?
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|l|}
\hline 4 & 2 & 3 & 2 \\
\hline 3 & 3 & 1 & 2 \\
\hline 2 & 1 & 3 & 1 \\
\hline 1 & 2 & 1 & 2 \\
\hline \multicolumn{4}{|c|}{ front }
\end{tabular}
<image1>

Three-digit powers of 2 and 5 are used in this ''cross-number'' puzzle. What is the only possible digit for the outlined square?
\begin{tabular}{lcl}
\textbf{ACROSS} & & \textbf{DOWN} \\
\textbf{2}. $2^m$ & & \textbf{1}. $5^n$
\end{tabular}
<image1>

solution:
First, see that we can place $5 	imes$ on the grid. Start with one $	imes$ in any location. Fix a direction, make one knight's move away in that direction and place another $	imes$. Repeat three times. The result looks like this:
 egin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline$	imes$ & $\cdot$ & & & $\cdot$ \n\hline$\cdot$ & $\cdot$ & $	imes$ & & $\cdot$ \n\hline & & & & $	imes$ \n\hline & $	imes$ & & & \n\hline$\cdot$ & $\cdot$ & & $	imes$ & $\cdot$ \n\hline
\end{tabular}

Next, we see that we can't have more than 5 . Suppose we did. Then by pigeonhole, at least one column has at least two $	imes$ in it. In the remainder, we show that if some column has two $	imes$, then there are at most $4 	imes$ in the whole grid.

Notice that a column may not have more than two $	imes$ in it. Furthermore, if one column has two $	imes$, then the adjacent columns must be empty. Then there are two columns not adjacent to the column which has two $	imes$ in it. If either column has two $	imes$, then the other is empty. Therefore, there are at most two $	imes$ among them.

Very easy casework shows that up to rotation and reflection, there are three types of paths in
        total, of the following forms: Among all paths of the first kind, the one with the minimal weight has weight
        16 + 11 + 17 + 14 + 3 + 19 + 3 + 9 + min{4 - max{16, 11}, 2 - max{17, 14}, . . . }
        which is 77 by inspection. Among all paths of the second kind, the one with the minimal weight has weight
min{9 + 3 + 19 + 3 + 4 + 2 + min{16 + 17, 11 + 14}, 3 + 9 + 16 + 11 + 8 + 2 + min{19 + 14, 3 + 17}, . . . }
which is 65 by inspection. Among all paths of the third kind, the one with the minimal weight has weight
min{3 + 9 + 8 + 4 + 14 + 17 + min{3 + 16, 19 + 11}, 16 + 11 + 4 + 2 + 3 + 19 + min{9 + 14, 3 + 17}}
which is 74 by inspection. Thus, the minimum weight spanning path has weight 65 .

